
=============================
sudo nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24
=============================
Replace 192.168.1.0/24 with your network's subnet. The -sn flag tells nmap to only discover hosts and not port scan them.

Slow and Steady Port Scan:
Android devices can be picky about scan speed, and a fast scan might cause them to drop packets or fail to respond. 
To ensure you get results without overwhelming the device, use a slow timing template and limit the packet rate.

===================================================
sudo nmap -sS -p- --max-rate 100 -T2 <IP_OF_PHONE>
===================================================
-sS: Performs a TCP SYN scan (stealth scan), which is nmap's default for root users and less likely to be logged than a full TCP connect scan.
-p-: Scans all 65,535 TCP ports. Android devices typically have few open ports, but this is thorough.
--max-rate 100: Limits the scan to sending no more than 100 packets per second, which is crucial 
for discovering sensitive devices like some Android phones.
-T2: Uses the "Polite" timing template, which further slows down the scan to reduce network load and avoid detection.
Service and Version Detection:
If you find open ports, you'll want to know what services are running on them.

==================================================
sudo nmap -sV -sC --max-rate 50 -T2 <IP_OF_PHONE>
==================================================
-sV: Probes open ports to determine service and version information^9.
-sC: Runs default, safe scripts to gather more information (like HTTP titles or SSL details). 
This is a good balance of useful information without being overly intrusive.
What You Should Be Looking For
Open Ports: On a standard Android phone, you should expect very few, if any, open ports. Common findings might be:
Port 5555: Sometimes open for Android Debug Bridge (ADB), though this is usually disabled by default.
Ports associated with apps: Some apps, like file sharing apps (e.g., certain FTP or media server apps), may open ports on the local networK.
Chromecast/mirroring services: These can open ports for local discovery and streaming.
Operating System Fingerprinting: Use the -O flag to try and identify the OS. Nmap may correctly identify it as Android or a Linux-based system.

=============================================
sudo nmap -O --max-rate 50 -T2 <IP_OF_PHONE>
=============================================
MAC Address: During the initial host discovery (-sn scan), note the MAC address and its vendor (e.g., Samsung Electronics).
This confirms you're scanning the right device1.
What to Avoid to Not Upset the Router
Your main goal is to be a "good neighbor" on your own network. Aggressive scanning can trigger router-level security features,
cause instability, or just slow everything down for everyone.

Avoid Aggressive Timing: Do not use -T4 (Aggressive) or -T5 (Insane). These templates send packets as fast as possible 
and can easily overwhelm a consumer-grade router like a Verizon Fios unit, leading to slowdowns or temporary disconnections for other devices.
Avoid Massive Scans of the Entire Subnet: Running a full port scan (-p-) with service detection (-sV) on every single IP
in your subnet (192.168.1.0/24) is a bad idea. It generates a huge amount of traffic in a short time. Always scan a specific target IP once you've identified it.
Avoid Intrusive NSE Scripts: Nmap's Scripting Engine (NSE) is powerful, but some scripts are disruptive. 
Avoid using script categories like intrusive, dos (Denial of Service), exploit, or brute unless you know exactly what you're doing
and are prepared for potential consequences. Stick to the default or safe categories, which are used by the -sC flag.
Limit Your Scan Rate: As shown in the commands above, using --max-rate is your best tool for controlling the impact on the network. Start low (e.g., 100 packets/sec)
and only increase it if you must.
Scan During Off-Peak Hours: If you must run a more intensive scan, do it when no one else is actively using the network for streaming, gaming, or video calls.
By following these slower, more targeted commands, you can successfully gather information about
your Android phone without causing problems for your network or your router.
